===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To follow behind (someone or something); to tail (someone or something).
#: {{ux|en|The hunters '''trailed''' their prey deep into the woods.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To drag (something) behind on the ground.
#: {{ux|en|You'll get your coat all muddy if you '''trail''' it around like that.}}
#* '''1922''', {{w|Virginia Woolf}}, ''{{w|Jacob's Room}}'' Chapter 1
#*: "I saw your brother—I saw your brother," he said, nodding his head, as Archer lagged past him, '''trailing''' his spade, and scowling at the old gentleman in spectacles.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To leave (a trail of).
#: {{ux|en|He walked into the house, soaking wet, and '''trailed''' water all over the place.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To show a [[trailer]] of (a film, TV show etc.); to release or publish a preview of (a report etc.) in advance of the full publication.
#: {{ux|en|His new film was '''trailed''' on TV last night.}}
#: {{ux|en|There were no surprises in this morning's much-'''trailed''' budget statement.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To hang or drag loosely behind; to move with a slow sweeping motion.
#: ''The bride's long dress '''trailed''' behind her as she walked down the aisle.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[run]] or [[climb]] like certain [[plant]]s.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To drag oneself lazily or reluctantly along.
#: ''Our parents marched to church and we '''trailed''' behind.''
# To be [[lose|losing]], to be behind in a competition.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 29, 2011|author=Keith Jackson|work=Daily Record
|title=[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/celtic/2011/12/29/spl-celtic-1-rangers-0-86908-23665738/ SPL: Celtic 1 Rangers 0]
|passage=Neil Lennon and his players have, in almost no time at all, roared back from '''trailing''' Rangers by 15 points in November to ending the year two points clear.}}
# {{lb|en|military}} To carry (a firearm) with the [[breech]] near the ground and the upper part inclined forward, the piece being held by the right hand near the middle.
# To flatten (grass, etc.) by walking through it; to tread down.
#: {{rfquotek|Longfellow}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} To take advantage of the ignorance of; to impose upon.
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars}} {{w|Charlotte Brontë}}
#*: I presently perceived she was (what is vernacularly termed) '''trailing''' Mrs. Dent; that is, playing on her ignorance.

